❄️Study Tips for Holidays at Home: 
1️⃣ Make a study plan, be realistic on what you can accomplish
2️⃣ Reviews with a friend to hold you accountable
3️⃣ Study early in the morning to avoid distractions and start the day off productive 
4️⃣ Don’t miss out on family time — time is precious, you won’t get it back. Take the time to get a few things on your list accomplished but do not fill guilty about spending time with the ones you love. 
5️⃣ Don’t complain about school or clinic,  it’s hard and stressful but be grateful on where you’re at, no one wants negativity.

taking a minute to give myself a high five because today I got through all of the KMK NBEO Part I material once 😅😂 I set a goal for myself to get through everything before Christmas. I know myself, and know that I need to review the material at least 3 times before it clicks with me. With right at 3 months until test date, it’s crunch time and time to buckle down. I now feel like I’ve “scoped” each subject at length and time to solidify all the concepts even further. Let’s go!

And to all the other OD3 studying, hang in there. Keep pushing. Tough times don’t last but tough people do. 💪🏼

I’m asked a lot of the time when I’m studying why do I take hand written summaries sometimes and charts/outlines other times. To be honest, I get bored when studying and sometimes drawing things out really helps to stimulate my brain and keep me focused on what I’m studying.

However studying for NBEO Part I has changed this for me. I spent a lot of time drawing things out for subjects like anatomy but quickly realized how time consuming that can become.

Something I’ve found to work for me is to draw things out when I’m reviewing for a second time to summarize the highlights or when I’m studying topics that aren’t sticking. Like the actions of EOMs.. I know this topic is covered in several sections and it’s important to know it that like the back of my hand. So I’ve made a quick summary sheet to have when I’m reviewing.

Have you guys heard of Focus Sprints? I've recently learned about this phrase from one of Matthew Encina's videos (@matthewencina @thefuturishere). It's simply taking 90 minutes to cut off all distractions, placing everything on do not disturb mode and setting a timer for 90 minutes.

Create a goal that you want to get done during this sprint and go. This time is set aside for focus and getting intense work done.

I've recently been adding these sprints into my study routines and have seen tremendous amount of success. I always have these bing plans for my day but at the end of the evening, I NEVER get everything finished. This has really helped me buckle in and set goals for my study sessions. I get distracted somewhat easily but knowing after 90 minutes, I can take a 10-20 minute break after gets me through. Theres something that's so motivating about being timed that just works.

I really recommend trying Focus Sprints this week. Whether it's 60 minutes of focusing or only 25, it could really be the kick in pants you need to GET STUFF DONE.

Something I’ve always told myself was, “If everyone else can do it, so can you” I read an article on Medium that really resonated with me, it said “the people you observe from a distance are no different from you. You have the same opportunity as them and you can be just like them, but you’ll never be exactly them. You may seek their results but your journey will be different. But there’s nothing stopping you... you can work as hard and learn to network just as well. You can endure the pain of setback or the disappointment of failure. You can fall down and get back up again. You can inspire people with your stories, or help a stranger who reminds you of your former self.” If everyone else can do it... what is stopping YOU.
your time isn’t slipping away, your energy is. Go.

Everyone experiences bad days. Some days, you’ll spend sulking in self-pity over minor setbacks, rejection, and life’s general unfairness. Each minute you spend in despair, robs you of productivity and happiness. It sucks the time out of what you could be directing your time and energy, so next time you’re feeling down, reflect on your passion, your growth and your relationships. If everyone else can do this, you can too.

What’s your finals week comforts? I had about 3,000 finals weeks at this point and I’ve found out that I feel at home studying in just about any coffee shop listening to my ‘study sans words’ playlist. I also love wearing thick socks in the winter and pop on a flannel for extra comfort. It’s the little things that makes the stress better.
finals week, we meet again baby. Be good to us 😅 on the plus side, 6 days until I’m in Cabo 🙌🏼

when you walk out of the door each morning, take a deep breath — hold up your head and remind yourself why you started, think of your goals, thing about your big picture. Do your best, and stop being so damn hard on yourself. Keep trying, keep falling down, learn from each hump in the road and GET BACK UP. You’re doing the best you can

Matt Howell | 3rd Year | Texarkana, TX 👁
“For me, optometry school has been a long lesson on the importance of perspective. Some things are simply a given: boring lectures, exhausting weeks, unfair exams, poorly organized assignments, bad professors, tough patients, ridiculous schedules, low grades, etc etc etc. You have NO control over those things. However, there’s one thing you DO have control over, your perspective. The lenses (pun intended) in which we view every moment is a CHOICE. You can choose to dread class/clinic every day (which is very easy to do). OR you can choose to recognize what a blessing it is to have the opportunity to become a doctor! Literally billions of people would kill to be in our positions and to learn the incredible things we learn. You could choose to be mad when a proctor gives excessively harsh feedback on your clinical skills. OR you could choose to see it as an opportunity to grow and improve. See what I’m getting at? Choose to be an opportunist, not a victim. I realize that this attitude towards life isn’t easy or even natural. But it’s worth it! What have you ever gained or accomplished through anxiety? Nothing. It’s a waste of your precious time and energy! Look for that silver lining in all situations and I promise that OD school can be fun.”

I love reading (obsessing) over productivity tips and goal settings, I've recently found: The best productivity hacks are in the questions you are not asking, sometimes they are right in your back pocket:
- What actions led to your biggest achievements last week?
- Can you repeat them this week?
- What seems to interrupt you every day?
- What distracted you the most yesterday?
- What were the intentions you set last week?
- Which of them did you get done? And why?
